<font color="#FF0000">WAR'S OWN PROTEST</font><br>
<tt>Mon Jul  7 23:34:26 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
<br>
From the unpublished book based on the diary I kept in Viet Nam, June 67-July68;<br><br>
Many believe war's appetite is violence, appeased with death and destruction.<br><br>
But War gives birth to respect and honor, glory and shame. <br>
It reeks with compassion in times of suffering and pain.  <br>
It fosters trust and love amidst joys and sorrows. <br><br>
Yet, War's greatest power and its most forgotten gift is the friendship it cultivates. <br>
In the middle of chaos and destruction, fighting and dying, War shares with us this precious gift.<br><br>
Without prejudice it shares its glory with any who dare to taste its pains, sorrows and shame. <br><br>
It's only there one touches eternal joys, peace and victory.<br>

